{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_dexter_ver01/data/42047197/00340588678/1946040101/0406.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE 6\nHospitalized Veterans Visit Convention\nHHpJ\nf n Mses\n\u25a0I&JHB\u00abi I t s\n8 fit \u2019k gR mRHbSk\n>^^^7rm\nf l/.'V \u25a0l. v itJ\u201e l~\u2018 ;,i \u2018V f I\ngj |BB he sm\u00df mBS fIHHBK\nS y\u00a3 SHgfiHfl\u00df HnnraHggS :t,, 'A.'& -v\nW 1\nf i^Ut HE I**\nf\u00bb BjMKgB lit ik.\\ i&r&^V'&igvi.\nb\u00bbHI i\nvs* MB WBH \u25a0VJHHBwRwMHBHBBUB BtaHHlhk. MMs\nFour hospitalized vets appeared before the convention delegates to plead their cases for\nautomobiles for some thousands of paraplegics who are in army and navy hospitals through\nout the country. Paraplegics are permanently paralyzed, losing the power of both legs. Pic\ntured above are Lt. Zelner, Sgt. Egner, Pvt. Lee and Sgt. Don Murray. Their plea for the\nautomobiles resulted in the UAW taking the first step in this direction by contributing three\nfull-equipped autos with special devices for paralyzed vets to be placed at the disposal of\nvarious veterans\u2019 hospitals.\n\u2014A UAW Photo.\nPassed By Convention\nUAW Veterans Program\n1. Thnt the Veterans\u2019Department\nof the International Union be un\nder the direction of the Interna\ntional President, who shnll appoint\na veteran as Departmental Direc\ntor. The International Executive\nBoard shall assign the Veterans'\nDepartment such staff as is neces\nsary to properly carry out its func\nt ions.\n\n2. Each Regional Director shall\ndesignate a member of his staff\nwho shall be a veteran and who\nshall be charged with the responsi\nbility of co-ordinating the unions\nveteran activities within said re\ngion.\nSuch Regional Veterans\u2019 Repre\nsentative shnll be under the direc\ntorship of their respective Regional\nDirector and shall act ns liaison\nreperesentative between the re\ngion and the Veterans\u2019 Depart\nment on all veteran activities.\n\n3. The Regional Veterans\u2019 Repre\nsentative shall hold periodic con\nferences of veterans to discuss\nveterans problems and enunciate\nprograms within the region.\n\nThe International Veterans\u2019 De\npartment shall call, on authoriza\ntion of the International Executive\nBoard, such periodic veterans con\nferences as are necessary.\n\n4. Call upon the Veterans Ad\nministration to absorb, as soon as\npossible all present Army hospitals\nas soon as available, for the pur\npose of hospitalizing discharged vet\nerans who are, at the present time,\nwaiting for such hospitalization;\nand that such hospitals be under\nthe direct supervision of the Vet\nerans Administration. Also Veter\nans Administration maintnin At\nlantic City, Bay of Tines and other\nresorts ns recuperation centers for\ndisabled veterans and if necessarv\nexpand the program to localities\nwhich would tend to speed up the\nrecuperation and that all such hos\npitals and recuperation centers\nshall not discriminate as to race,\ncreed, and color.\n\n5. That such specialized prob\nlems of veterans as employment\nand education or vocational train\ning be handled by government\nagencies whose background of ex\nperience best enables them to\nhandle them, rather than dumping\nall veterans\u2019 problems into the al\nready over taxed Veterans Admin\nistration; that employment be\nhandled through the United States\nEmployment Service, education and\nvocational training through the\nU. S. Ottice of Education and co\noperating state agencies (partially\nprovided in GI Bill of Rights).\n\n6. Call upon Congress to amend\nthe present GI Bill of Rights to\nmake payable Unemployment bene\nfits to discharged veterans where\never a strike is in progress, brought\nabout by failure of the employer to\ncomply with existing laws govern\ning wages, hours, working condi\ntions or failure of employers to\nbargain collectively in good faith.\nPromote amendment in state leg\nislatures of existing unemployment\nlaws to give the veteran credit for\nmoney earned of n base period\nprior to his entering the armed\nforces so as to enable him to draw\nstate unemployment compensation,\nprior to that under the GI Bill.\n7. Endorse and promote the\npassage of Senator Wagner\u2019s Bill\nto give all members in the armed\nforces and the merchant marine\ncredit of $l6O per month to their\nsocial security account for every\nmonth or fraction thereof spent in\nsuch service.\n\n8. Promote an increase of 30%\nin pensions to all disabled veterans\nand make any further increases as\nthe conditions of the cost of living\nchanges.\n\n9. Expansion of education and\nvocational training opportunities,\nat Government expense, to all vet\nerans of World War II (as pro\nvided in the GI Bill of Rights) so\nthat the veteran shall receive a\nsubsistence allowance of SIOO with\nan additional $25 per month for\neach dependent. This allowance\nshall be increased accordingly at\nany time there occurs a change in\nthe marital status of the veteran\nduring the period of his education\nor training.\n\n10. (1> Adjusted service pay to\nall veterans based on length and\nplace of service; $3 per day for do\nmestic service; $4 for each day of\nactive overseas service; minimum I\nUNITED AUTOMOBILE WORKER\nCOMPETITIVE\nSHOP DEPT.\nIS EXPANDED\nAggressive action to organize\nshops which are competitive with\nthose already organized by the\nUAW-CIO was ordered by the At\nlantic City Convention. The exist\ning understaffed department was\nordered augmented on the basis\nthat each member of the Interna\ntional Executive Board shall name\ntwo members of the organizing\nstaff. All appointments are subject\nto the approval of the Interna\ntional President and board.\nThe incoming President and In\nternational Executive Board were\ninstructed that all provisions of the\nInternational Constitution as re\nlated to the Competitive Shop De\npartment shall be rigidly and strict\nly enforced.\nof SIOO and maximum of $3500 for\nthose performing no overseas serv\nice; minimum of SSOO and maxi\nmum of $4500 for those who served\noverseas.\n\n(2) Promote and coordinate the\nsupport of the veterans organiza\ntions towards the passage of the\nadjustment pay bill and also the\nbill pertaining to enlisted men ter\nminal leave (a privilege now\ngranted to officers).\n\n11. No initiation fees or rein\nstatement fees for World War II\nveterans (already provided by\nUAW-CIO Constitution and Execu\ntive Board action).\n\n12. Promote and endorse the\nfull employment program as out\nlined by the Natfonal CIO.\n\n13. Constructive cooperat ion\nwith the rank and file and liberal\nand progressive elements of all ex\nisting veterans organizations to aid\nveterans rehabilitation; continued\nstudy of possibility of endorsing\none particular veterans organiza\ntion.\n\nTHEREFORE BE IT RE\nSOLVED: That this Tenth Annual\nConvention of the UAW-CIO does\nhereby go on record\" endorsing this\nprogram as the policy of the vet\nerans department for the forth\ncoming year.\nConvention\nRaises Dues\nConstitutional steps to\nstrengthen the financial posi\ntion of the International Union\nwere among the more impor\ntant recommendations of the\nConstitution Committee of the\nTenth Annual Convention that\nwere adopted.\n\nMonthly dues were increased\nfrom SI.OO to $1.50 Heretofore the\ndues were divided 60 cents to the\nlocal union and 40 cents to the In\nternational, and of the latter 5\ncents was allocated to the United\nAutomobile Worker and 2V\u00a3 cents\nfor education and recreation. Un\nder the new constitution 85 cents\ngoes to local and 65 cents* to\nthe International. Of the latter 5\ncents is allocated to a new fund,\nthe International Strike Fund, 5\ncents to the Auto Worker, 2V6\ncents to education and recreation,\nand 1 cent to the new Fair Prac\ntices and Anti-Discrimination De\npartment of the International Un\nion. The increase in dues is ef\nfective for April 1946 dues.\n\nThe convention also approved a\nspecial International assessment of\n$1 per member payable during the\nmonths of May, June or July 1946,\nfor the International Union Strike\nFimd. The assessment provides a\nsubstantial foundation for the In\nternational Strike Fund, and the\nfund will be added to steadily by\nthe 5 cents allocation from the in\ncreased monthly dues. The assess\nment permitted another substan\ntial distribution of money from the\nInternational to the locals which\nhave been on strike, to be made\nfrom the general fund.\nA further substantial saving was\nmade by the convention when it\napproved a recommendation that\nthe Eleventh International Con\nvention be held in September 1947,\nthus providing an interim of 17\nmonths between the Tenth and\nEleventh Conventions. The dele\ngates went on record as favoring\nSan Francisco as first choice for\nthe convention city, with Louis\nville, Kentucky, as second choice.\nOne of the most important rec\nommendations of the Constitution\nCommittee which was adopted was\nsetting up the Fair Practices and\nAnti-Discrimination Department\nas a constitutional department,\nwith the allocation of one cent a\nmonth per capita from the Inter\nnational per capita tax to finance\nit. The International President ap\npoints the director or administra\ntive assistant who will conduct the\noperation of the department and\nalso appoints a supervisory com\nmittee of International Executive\nBoard members for it. No limit\nwas set on the membership of this\ncommittee. On the local union lev\nel, the constitution now makes it\nmandatory that each local set up\na Fair Practices and Anti-Discrim\nination Committee in the local.\nAn important change in local un\nion election procedure was the\nadoption of a constitutional change\nrequiring that the election of ex\necutive officers of a local union\nMUST be by majority vote. Many\nlocals have elected their officers in\nthe past by plurality rather than\nby majority, sometimes resulting in\na minority candidate being elect\ned. The constitution was also\nchanged to prevent a local union\nexecutive officer from holding more\nthan one office. This ends the fair\nly common practice of a two or\nthree-year trustee running for an\nother office without resigning as a\ntrustee.\n\nAnother important change is one\nin which the International Union\ndesignate the UAW-CIO Interna\ntional and local union as his exclu\nsive agent to appear and act for\nhim and in his behalf before any\nboard, court, committee or other\ntribunal in any manner affecting\nhis status as an employe or as a\nmtaMrttfMWk*!\nA Change in\nOut of Work\nReceipt Plan\nAn important change easing\nthe constitutional provision un\nder which members who are\nlaid off or sick are required to\nobtain \u201cOut of Work\u201d receipts\nto maintain their union mem\nbership was made by the At\nlantic City Convention. The\nConstitution Committee recom\nmended the following in place\nof Article 16, Section 19, and\nit was adopted:\nAny member becoming out of\nwork for any reason shall report\nhis unemployment in person, by\nwritten communication or tele\ngrsftn to the financial secretary of\nthe Local Union within one (1>\nmonth from the date he became\nunemployed. The financial secre\ntary shall issue to such member an\nofficial memorandum indicating the\ndate upon which the member be\ncame unemployed, provided, that\nno such memorandum shall be is\nsued to the member unless he\nshall have paid all dues and assess\nments owing by him at the time\nhe became unemployed. Such mem\nber shall be entitled to \u201cout of\nwork\u201d receipts bearing the words\n\u201cout of work\" or the letter \u201cO/W\"\nupon application made by him\nwithin one month after his re\nemployment or at any time dur\ning his period of unemployment,\nprovided that he is eligible to re\nceive the same under the provi\nsions of this section, Such member\nshall be exempt from dues-pay\nments for the period of his unem\nployment, provided that he shall\nhave reported his reemployment\nin person, by written communica\ntion or telegram to the financial\nsecretary of the Local Union with\nin one (1) month from the date\nhe became re-employed arid pro\nvided that he had not worked on\nany compensable job forty (40) or\nmore hours in any calendar month\nof unemployment. In the event a\nmember fails to report either his\nunemployment or re-employment\nwithin the respective one (1) month\nperiods as provided herein, he shall\nnot be subject to any exemption,\nand shall be subject to all of the\nprovisions of this article which re\nlate to the obligation of members\nto pay dues.\nA delegate asked for the floor:\n\u201cDo I understand this correctly,\ndoes this mean if a man is out sick\nand notifies his financial secretary,\nif he is out of worjc for the follow\ning year he does not have to get\nhis O. W.\u2019s until he comes back to\nwork, at which time he can get\nthem all at one time? It that cor\nrect?\"\nCommittee Member Chase: \u201cThat\nis correct.\u201d\nFrankensteen Aims\nAt Congress\nATLANTIC CITY, N. J. Rich\nard T. Frankensteen, who has left\nhis vice-presidency of the United\nAuto Worker s-CIO, announced\nwhile here that he would seek the\nDemocratic nomination to Con\ngress from Michigan\u2019s 13th Dis\ntrict. Frankensteen recently was\nnarrowly defeated in his campaign\nto become mayor of Detroit.\nmember of the local or Interna\ntional Union. This was recommend\ned because under a recent Su\npreme Court decision involving the\nRailway Labor Act it has been\nheld that mere membership in a\nunion did not give the union the\npower to make final adjustment of\na dispute or a grievance with the\nemployer. This UAW-CIO consti\ntutional change will prevent any\nattempt by union-busters to at\ntempt individual bargaining, it was\nstated.\n\nThe constitutional allowance for\nInternational officers and represent\natives of sl2 a day for hotel room\nand meals while away from home\non union business was increased to\nsls a day.\nApril, 1946","height":"25242","width":"17376"}}
